{"id": "38131", 
"title": "Bug 38131ajc needs d . option while correctly compiling classes from subpackage", 
"description": "Bug 38131ajc needs d . I am using 1.1rc1. This is a regression since rc1 and a deviation from javac. I am guessing this may have to do something with change in the underlying Eclipse compiler. Create a class in a subpackage such as:

package subpackage;

public class Test {

  public static void main(String[] args) {
    System.out.println("Hello");
  }

}

Then compile using following command: ajc subpackage\Test.java

You will see a directory "subpackage" created under the existing "subpackage" directory. subpackage\Test.java or javac subpackage\Test.java.

No big deal, really. ", 
"OB": "When compiling a class in a subpackage using the command 'ajc subpackage\Test.java', a directory named 'subpackage' is created within the existing 'subpackage' directory. This causes an issue when running the Java command, resulting in an exception: 'Exception in thread "main" java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: subpackage/Test'.", 
"EB": "Running the 'ajc' command with the '-d .' option should correctly compile the classes from the subpackage, without creating an additional 'subpackage' directory.", 
"SR": "To reproduce the issue: 
1. Create a class in a subpackage.
2. Compile the class using the command 'ajc subpackage\Test.java'.
3. Run the Java command and observe the exception.

To resolve the issue, add the '-d .' option to the 'ajc' command when compiling the classes from the subpackage."}
